{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413068"},"attributes":{"position":2,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:55:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:55:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"600"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489134"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:06:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:06:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"600"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/600"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.13,0.68,0.09,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102953"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/600"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85419"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"89"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9900"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43020"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102953"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman is brought to a rural Emergency Department with a new onset left-sided throbbing headache which began 12 hours ago. The pain is also felt in the neck. She denies any visual disturbance, photophobia, nausea, vomiting, weakness, sensory, and speech disturbance. She also complains of ache in her shoulder joints and fatigue for several weeks. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 150/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, and temperature 36.8\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Her neurological examination is unremarkable. Her pupils are equal and reactive bilaterally. Mild tenderness is present on palpation over her scalp, worse in the temporal region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin: 110 g/L (115-160)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 10.5 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets: 420 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EC-reactive protein: 65 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT head","Temporal artery biopsy","High-dose oral prednisolone","Intravenous methylprednisolone","Methotrexate"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis woman presents with features highly suggestive of giant cell arteritis (GCA), including new onset headache, scalp tenderness, shoulder girdle aching, fatigue, anaemia, thrombocytosis, and raised inflammatory markers. The most important initial management is \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh-dose oral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E. Immediate corticosteroid therapy is critical to prevent irreversible complications such as vision loss. Treatment should not be delayed for further investigations, and oral corticosteroids are appropriate in the absence of visual symptoms or ischaemic complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Southend probability score (GCAPS) is a validated tool to estimate the likelihood of GCA, incorporating age, symptoms, and laboratory findings. In this case, the GCAPS is calculated as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAge 60-69 years: 0 points\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENew headache: +2\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EScalp tenderness: +3\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPolymyalgia rheumatica symptoms: +2\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECRP \u226530 mg/L: +3\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets \u2265400 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L: +2\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENo other diagnosis more likely: 0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal GCAPS: 12 points. A score \u22659 is highly suggestive of GCA, further supporting urgent steroid initiation, but scoring should not delay treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal artery biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for diagnosis. However, treatment should be commenced without waiting for biopsy results. Histological changes persist for at least one week after therapy is commenced, so a biopsy can still be performed after treatment has begun. Delaying steroids for biopsy risks permanent vision loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT head\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered if there is suspicion of intracranial pathology, but the absence of neurological deficits, visual symptoms, or features of raised intracranial pressure makes this less likely. The clinical picture and laboratory findings point towards GCA rather than an acute neurological event.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous methylprednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for patients with visual symptoms or threatened vision, such as acute visual loss or amaurosis fugax. In the absence of these features, high-dose oral corticosteroids are sufficient and preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E is a steroid-sparing agent that may be considered for long-term management in patients at risk of steroid-related adverse effects or with relapsing disease. It is not used as initial therapy in the acute setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGCA is a medical emergency due to the risk of irreversible vision loss. Prompt recognition and treatment with corticosteroids are essential, even before confirmatory testing. The Southend probability score (GCAPS) can help support the diagnosis but should not delay urgent management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter a medium or large-vessel vasculitis is diagnosed, classification into GCA is according to the 2022 American College of Rheumatology/EULAR Classification Criteria. This takes into account various clinical, laboratory, imaging, and biopsy criteria. Some of the imaging modalities included are temporal artery ultrasound (\u0027halo sign\u0027) and FDG-PET activity throughout the aorta.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Immediate initiation of corticosteroid therapy is essential in suspected giant cell arteritis (GCA) to prevent irreversible vision loss.","Oral corticosteroids are appropriate for initial management in the absence of visual symptoms or ischaemic complications.","The Southend probability score (GCAPS) can support clinical diagnosis but should not delay urgent treatment."],"references":["Baig I, Pascoe A, Kini A, Lee A. Giant cell arteritis: early diagnosis is key. Eye Brain [Internet]. 2019Jan17 [cited 2020Apr28]; Available from:\u00a0https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6340646/","Davies CG, May DJ. The role of temporal artery biopsies in giant cell arteritis. The Royal College of Surgeons of England [Internet]. 2011Jan [cited 2020Apr28]; Available from:\u00a0https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3293260/","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Polymyalgia rheumatica and giant cell arteritis. In: Therapeutic Guidelines [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2023 [cited 2025 May 17]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au/","Laskou F, Coath F, Mackie SL, Banerjee S, Aung T, Dasgupta B. A probability score to aid the diagnosis of suspected giant cell arteritis. Clin Exp Rheumatol. 2019 Mar-Apr;37 Suppl 117(2):104-108. Epub 2019 Feb 15. PMID: 30767870. Available from: https://www.clinexprheumatol.org/abstract.asp?a=13113","Ponte C, Grayson PC, Robson JC, Suppiah R, Gribbons KB, Judge A, Craven A, Khalid S, Hutchings A, Watts RA, Merkel PA, Luqmani RA; DCVAS Study Group. 2022 American College of Rheumatology/EULAR Classification Criteria for Giant Cell Arteritis. Arthritis Rheumatol. 2022 Dec;74(12):1881-1889. doi: 10.1002/art.42325. Epub 2022 Nov 8. PMID: 36350123. Available from: https://ard.eular.org/article/S0003-4967(24)08730-2/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85419"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"600"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85419"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-17T16:27:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-17T16:29:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"600"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102953"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type